The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Balaji Telefilms has posted a 25 per cent lower net profit for the financial year ended March 31 at Rs 41.2 crore compared with Rs 55.40 crore last fiscal. The board has recommended a payout of Rs 16 per share as the final dividend for the year. The total income of the company last fiscal has increased to Rs 201.68 crore from Rs 184.44 crore in 2003-04. For the fourth quarter ended March 31, the company has clocked a Rs 9.64-crore net profit compared with Rs 12.33 crore in the corresponding period of the previous fiscal. 

 India Trade Promotion Organisation (ITPO) will set up a 5,000-sq-m exhibition centre at Guwahati by 2006. The regional centre in the Northeast is expected to promote trade and commerce with the Asean region and China and emerge as a regional trade hub. The work for the centre is currently on in full swing. It will be able to hold trade fairs and exhibitions from next year. 

 Acer India will invest $3 million in this calendar year to beef up its retail operations in the country. The company has already invested about 30 per cent of the amount. The company is targeting to increase its retail outlets to 200 this year from 165 at present, out of which 60 will be exclusive Acer malls. 

 Simplex Concrete Piles has bagged a Rs 208.50-crore contract from Jindal Power in Chhattisgarh. The contract is for civil and structural work for 4 x 250 MW (phase 1) Raigarh thermal power project at Tamnar in Chhattisgarh.

 Capgemini, a technology and outsourcing services provider, will set up its third facility in Mumbai, taking the company?s India offshore capacity to 3,000 seats. The new facility, spread over a 60,000 sq ft area, will be located in Vikhroli, a central suburb of Mumbai, with a capacity of 740 seats. It will provide technology and outsourcing services to clients globally, Capgemini India?s chief executive Baru Rao said.

 Malaysia Airlines Engineering has signed a pact with Aviation Partners Boeing (APB) for setting up a regional modification centre. This will bring the country a step closer to being a regional aviation maintenance hub. The centre ? first of its kind in Southeast Asia ? will install fuel-saving wing extensions on Boeing 737 aircraft.

 TTK Prestige has got the approval to use its flagship brand ? Prestige ? in the United States. This will help TTK market its products under this brand name to the ethnic population there. So far, the company was selling its pressure cookers in the US under the brand Mantra.

